<HEAD>Survey: One In Six Britons Can't Find Own Country on Map</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One in six Britons questioned in a survey could n't find his own country on a map, and more than 40 percent had a big problem figuring a simple restaurant check, a newspaper reported Sunday One person even thought President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> leads <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s socialist <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, although 90 percent correctly identified the opposition leader as <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinnock </PERSON>, the survey found The survey of 994 people, published in <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sunday </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION>, was conducted last month by Market and <ORGANIZATION> Opinion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>. The newspaper commissioned it to test knowledge of geography, mathematics, common foreign language phrases, spelling, history, science and current affairs. The newspaper said the 18-question test was `` simple,'' but `` many of the replies were enough to break traditional teachers' hearts. The survey found 83 percent of the sample population could find <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> on a world map, but 7 percent had no idea where to look. Others placed it off the coast of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, off <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, in the <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> or in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Asked to spell `` embarrass,'' `` satellite'' and `` exercise,'' one in 10 immediately `` threw up their hands in defeat,'' the newspaper said. Fifty-nine percent spelled `` embarrass'' and `` satellite'' incorrectly, and 28 percent failed `` exercise.'' Mathematics added to the problem, the newspaper said. Asked to add menu prices for the total cost of a hamburger, french fries, apple pie and coffe