<HEAD>Soviet Communist Says KGB Could Learn Something From FBI</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> secret police could learn from the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> by telling Soviet citizens when they are being followed or monitored by its agents, one <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> member says. The campaign for `` glasnost,'' or openness on selected topics, has allowed the publication of some unusual items in Soviet media recently. But a letter in the latest issue of the Ogonyok weekly is believed to be the first suggestion to <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> secret police officers to look to the West for inspiration. Under President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, the government reportedly is working on a new statute regulating the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, or <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> from its Russian-language initials. But the powerful and secretive agency itself remains virtually above criticism in the state-run press. <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rachkov </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, who identified himself as a <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> member, wrote to tell the weekly that one of his friends, <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON>, started to wonder why he was never sent abroad on business trips by the government agency he works for. When <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> signed up for a tourist trip to <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, the vacation reservations were canceled two days before departure `` under a clearly invented pretext,'' <PERSON> Rachkov </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> came to believe that someone made a `` slanderous report'' about him to the <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> that ruined his chances of ever traveling outside the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. But he had no way of making anyone in authorit