<HEAD>President Orders Release Of Minors Arrested During Revolt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Chadli </PERSON> <PERSON> Bendjedid </PERSON> ordered the release on Sunday of about 500 minors arrested in a week of rioting over the worsening economy, the government announced. In addition, the president suspended all hearings before the special courts set up to try the youths, most of whom were arrested for looting and acts of vandalism during the unrest that began Oct. 4. The government has said 180 people died in the rioting, but unofficials reports said at least 500 people died and more than 1,000 were injured. The government also ordered the release Sunday of all those imprisoned during the unrest who were not directly involved in the revolt and those `` arrested for crimes of opinion.'' More than 3,000 people were reported arrested in <LOCATION> Algiers </LOCATION> and provincial cities during the riots over shortages, high food prices and the government's program of austerity and economic reform. Schools reopened Saturday, and the country was relatively calm. Those still held in prison will `` benefit fully of the rights of defense in accordance with the law,'' the government said. `` No judgment will be pronounced other than in the strict respect of legality.'' <PERSON> Miloud </PERSON> <PERSON> Brahimi </PERSON>, the president of <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>, last week protested the special tribunals, which he charged with violating the fundamental rights of presumed innocence. Also on Sunday, Interior Minister <PERSON> El-Hadi </PERSON> <PERSON> Khediri </PERSON> announced a nationwide revision of electoral lists as a first step to the Nov. 3 referendum that is to launch Bendjedid's program to democratize his country. In the referendum, the citizens will be asked to approve a revision of the constitution that would make the future prime minister answerable to <ORGANIZATION> Parliament