<HEAD>Campaign '88: Emotional Issues Rule the Race</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Another in a series on key issues in the presidential race.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It's been a down-and-dirty presidential campaign, from gleeful Democratic denunciations of <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> as a wimp to the Republicans' skewering of <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> over crime, the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> and the Pledge of Allegiance. While the dismal tenor of this year's campaign discourse has elicited groans from past presidents <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, political analysts credit <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> with tapping some of the same emotional issues that helped <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> capture the White House in 1968 and 1972 and laid the groundwork for <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s twin landslides of the 1980s. Some experts say it is a serious mistake for the Democrats, who have lost four of the past five presidential elections, to underestimate the seriousness with which the electorate responds to emotional appeals to its patriotism or fear of crime. The gut issues, symbolic or not, are real issues for many voters. `` Politics is a matter of gut responses, otherwise known as emotions,'' said <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Masters </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Dartmouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> professor of government. `` It's not just media manipulation,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Georgetown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> associate professor of government and expert on media and politics. `` If the Democrats continue to believe that symbolic issues do n't matter, they're going to foul up time and time again.'' <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Hess </PERSON>, a senior fellow at the <ORGANIZATION> Brookings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION>, said symbolic issues loom larger in this election because `` American politics, like nature, abhors a vacuum. The candidates seemed quite deliberately to choose not to face up to the pragmatic issues.'' <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said the race unfolded during a time of economic prosperity when there were few differences between Democrats and Republicans on dealing with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` When you subtract the issues of peace and prosperity, you leave very little, so we are left to fight on those gut isues of symbolic issues,'' he said. Conservative analyst <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>, publisher of the American Political Report, said, `` The Republicans have replayed the key cultural and patriotic issues with the swing voters that got the Republican presidential majority started in 1968 and 1972 and 1980.'' The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign flogged the crime spree of <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Horton </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> lifer who escaped while on a weekend furlough from prison, and pummeled <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> for being a self-proclaimed, card-carrying member of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>. In doing so, <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> said, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s people succeeded in rekindling in the minds of wavering <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> Democrats the emotions that `` pulled them to vote for Republican presidents in earlier years,'' while <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> failed to develop rival issues to appeal to the same swing voters. In their final debate last Thursday, both candidates sounded apologetic about the low-road campaigning. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, recalling the almost non-stop attacks the Democrats unleashed against him at their July convention in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, said, `` I do n't want to sound like a kid in the schoolyard -LRB- but -RRB- he started it.'' `` It was both ways,'' said <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Wattenberg </PERSON>, a senior fellow at the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. `` Two months ago, the best issue that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had on <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was ` wimp' and the best issue <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had on <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was ` L-word' -LRB- liberal -RRB-.'' The Republicans `` went after <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> on all the L-word stuff, which they had some nice symbols for _ prison furloughs and <ORGANIZATION> Pledge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Allegiance </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> and stuff like that. But it was n't about those issues,'' said <PERSON> Wattenberg </PERSON>, a Democrat. `` The reason they played was because they resonated in terms of 20 years of <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> history as too liberal,'' he said. `` It's not a small issue. It is haunting this party. It is which direction the plurality party in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> wants to take the country.'' On the other hand, the Democrats' wimp charge quickly lost its punch as <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> emerged from the GOP convention in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> as `` Captain Marvel,'' said <PERSON> Wattenberg </PERSON>. <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> said, `` By going hard-line on the cultural and patriotic issues, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> drove down the wimp factor. ... <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> put on a bit of a <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> outfit.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s highest negative rating in polls remains the perception that he is too close to the wealthy and too far from the middle class. But <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> failed to `` come on hard and tough and use economic populism and nationalism to get the guys in the bar in the ethnic sections of <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> or your dirt farmer in rural <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> angry at the Republicans.'' <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said, `` In a time of real prosperity, questions of economic justice and hostility toward big business do not cut it with the American public.'' As for such emotional issues as flag and country, `` you ca n't pretend that something that is an issue is not an issue,'' <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said `` It hurts the Democrats when they try to dismiss this in some way as bigotry or tasteless or un-American.'' `` It is an issue to Americans whether you wear your flag on your sleeve or whether you wear it on the seat of your pants,'' he said. `` Republicans are not only willing to wear their flag on their sleeves, they're willing to wear it on their foreheads. The Democrats are willing to move it off their keester, but they still want to keep it half covered, and Americans do n't like that.''
