<HEAD>Vietnam To Complete Partial Troop Withdrawal By December</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Cambodia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> said Sunday that it will complete its planned withdrawal of 50,000 military personnel from <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> on schedule in December. That would leave about 50,000 Vietnamese troops in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> has said it will remove all of its military forces from the neighboring country by 1990. The beginning of the formal withdrawal was conducted at a ceremony in June when <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> announced the withdrawal of its military command and some 13,000 soldiers. It said other army units left <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> in July, August and September. A joint communique issued Sunday by <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> and the Vietnamese-installed Cambodian government said: `` The remaining units will be withdrawn monthly from now to the end of 1988, and the last contingent of the 50,000 volunteers to be withdrawn in 1988 will be repatriated by land and water during the month of December.'' <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> invaded <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> in December 1978, ousted the radical communist <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> regime and installed another communist government. Communist forces defeated U.S.-backed governments in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> in the spring of 1975. The joint communique, carried by the official <ORGANIZATION> Vietnam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, welcomed representatives of foreign countries, international agencies and news organizations to observe the final stage of the first half of the withdrawal plan. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> is expected to pass again this year, for the 10th consecutive year, a resoludion demanding the pullout of all Vientmaese troops from <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. But a new element in the draft of this year's resolution calls for `` effective international supervision and control'' of the withdrawal. More than 1 million Cambodians were killed during the harsh rule of the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, and there is widespread fear that the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> will regain power if <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> pulls all of its forces out of the country. The <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> began a guerrilla campaign after it was ousted in 1978 and has the strongest military force in a coalition of groups fighting the Vietnamese and Cambodian grovernment troops.
