<HEAD>Rain Moves Across Nation's Midsection, Pacific Northwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Rainshowers and thunderstorms stretched across the nation's midsection ahead of a cold front Sunday, and rain also fell throughout the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> and parts of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> The cold front extended into the middle <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, and rain extended from <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, through <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> to western <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>. Rain showers were scattered from the northern Rockies west through the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> as a cold front settled across the region. The front was associated with a developing low pressure system that was moving southeast across central <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>. Winds gusted to 62 mph with blowing dust around Cody, <LOCATION> Wyo. </LOCATION>, and high winds were also reported in the northern <ORGANIZATION> Rockies </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> and parts of the <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> panhandle. Showers and a few thunderstorms were scattered over east-central and parts of southern <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. Rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT included nearly an inch at the Naval Air Station near <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, over a half inch at K.I. Sawyer Air Force Base near <LOCATION> Marquette </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION>; and <PERSON> Dillon </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mont </PERSON>. Temperatures were in the 60s or 70s across much of the nation Sunday afternoon. Temperatures were in the 50s from the northern Rockies through the <LOCATION> northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> and upper Great Lakes into the lower <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> where rain was falling. Readings were in the 40s over western <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>. Temperatures