<HEAD>Monday Showdown Promises Purge, But Won't Solve Crisis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS five grafs to include report that 14 Politburo members
may be replaced in shakeup. Picks up graf 4 pvs, `Tito dominated
...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An expected purge of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leadership will at best be only a start in trying to ease <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s worst crisis since World War II. The party <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> meets Monday to argue and approve what are billed as the most sweeping personnel changes in more than four decades in power. A Politburo member said Sunday that 14 of the 23 members of the ruling Politburo may be removed at the meeting of the policy-making <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. Four have announced their intention to resign and Politburo member <PERSON> Vasil </PERSON> <PERSON> Tupurkovski </PERSON> told reporters 10 others may be replaced. However radical the changes are at Monday's meeting, they will be only a stage in what one best-selling writer and dissident called the `` long agony'' of breaking with founding father <PERSON> Josip </PERSON> <PERSON> Tito </PERSON>. <PERSON> Tito </PERSON> dominated <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> for 35 years, ruling supreme until he died in May 1980. His portrait still hangs in almost every public room in the country and is carried fondly by some of the Serbian nationalists who have staged mass rallies throughout southern and eastern <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> in recent months. Their devotion to <PERSON> Tito </PERSON> is in some ways ironic, since they hope to restructure the ineffective political system <PERSON> Tito </PERSON> bequeathed his nation. Their demand for greater Serbian control over the Serbian republic's two autonomous provinces of <LOCATION> Vojvodina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> prompted the current political crisis. Serbian <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Slobodan </PERSON> <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON> has skillfully exploited the mass rallies. He has achieved national prominence on the wave of indignation Serbs feel about the alleged harassment of their fellow <PERSON> Christian </PERSON> <PERSON> Slavs </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>, the ancient Serbian kingdom that is now dominated by ethnic <PERSON> Albanians </PERSON>, who are mainly Moslem. In exploiting the rallies, <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON> has broken the order laid down by <PERSON> Tito </PERSON>, who gave broad autonomy to <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s six republics and two provinces and annually rotated national offices among them to prevent one region from dominating the others. <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON>'s drive has alarmed non-Serbian Communist leaders who fear the nation's largest ethnic group wants greater control over <LOCATION> Yugoslav </LOCATION> affairs. Yet they can not ignore his popularity in <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION> and the broader appeal of his calls for changes in the aging and sometimes ineffective ruling elite. On television and in newspaper columns last week, leaders engaged in an unprecedented public dispute over which leaders from which region will stand or fall when the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> replaces up to one-third of its 165 members at Monday's meeting. `` In these circumstances, it is easier to teach a whale to play the tambourine than to carry out the personnel changes,'' commented the <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION> daily <ORGANIZATION> Borba </ORGANIZATION>. The ethnic arguments are only part of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s problem. Unwise borrowing in the 1970s and the lack of a strong federal government to manage the economy have led to economic crisis, with the foreign debt at $ 21 billion and annual inflation at 217 percent. Living standards have fallen by one-half since 1980, and austerity measures adopted in May have slashed salaries while prices continue to rise. Striking workers have taken to the streets in increasing numbers, prompting the alarmed government to seek permission from the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> to relax the austerity program. The ethnic and economic arguments sometimes obscure the growing calls to abandon one-party rule and state-run economic management. The corruption in each Yugoslav republic angers the impoverished workers, and the verbose and tangled Communist jargon that surrounds most political pronouncements annoys even Communists themselves. After watching members of the national party Politburo and the <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> leadership debate for seven hours in <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>'s capital, <LOCATION> Pristina </LOCATION>, on Tuesday, the party leadership of the Serbian town of <LOCATION> Titovo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Uzice </LOCATION> commented, `` if the debate at Monday's meeting is dominated by the tenor of the one in <LOCATION> Pristina </LOCATION> ... then it had better be canceled.'' This frustration indicates the pressure for change in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>. But writer <PERSON> Dobrica </PERSON> <PERSON> Cosic </PERSON>, a wartime hero and former <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> purged by <PERSON> Tito </PERSON> in 1968, predicts that rearranging its political system will be a `` long agony.'' `` For decades, we have lived in a false situation,'' <PERSON> Cosic </PERSON> said in an interview. `` False standards, a false economy, a false unity, a false freedom. ... At some moment, the potentials of that fiction are exhausted, and that moment is approaching.''
</TEXT>
