<TEXT>
 Former Queen <PERSON> Farida </PERSON>, the divorced wife of <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>'s last king, <PERSON> Farouk </PERSON>, died Sunday of leukemia and other complications. She was 67. The former queen married King <PERSON> Farouk </PERSON> in 1938 when she was 17 and he was 18. They were divorced 11 years later. <PERSON> Farouk </PERSON> was toppled in a bloodless military coup in July 1952 and exiled to <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Farida </PERSON> lived mostly in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> in her later years and held a number of exhibits in <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>. In a coma for most of the past two weeks, she had suffered from leukemia, kidney inflammation and pneumonia. President <PERSON> Hosni </PERSON> <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON> ordered the state to pay her medical bills. She is survived by three daughters from her marriage with <PERSON> Farouk </PERSON>. Other details were not immediately available.
