<SECOND>AM-Tax Revolt, Bjt,0849</SECOND>
<HEAD>Decade-Old Tax Revolt Will Be Tested in November</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to correct category code</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Voters in half a dozen states face an eclectic mix of tax measures Nov. 8, from a steep hike in cigarette taxes to tax cuts reminiscent of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s decade-old Proposition 13. But there are signs the anti-tax fever that gripped the nation after Californians enacted Proposition 13 in June 1978 has cooled as inflation has eased, the economy has improved and taxpayers no longer feel so squeezed. Only in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> will voters decide issues this November that would force deep cuts in taxes. `` Voters are protecting what exists, but not going further. And in some cases, it looks like the electorate is willing to approve, more so than in the'70s or early'80s, very specific taxes for specific purposes,'' said <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> McGuigan </PERSON>, editor of the Free Congress Initiative and Referendum Report, a monthly newsletter published in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Californians, for example, will consider a measure to raise cigarette taxes by 25 cents a pack, using proceeds to promote health. The tax revolt peaked in the late 1970s and early 1980s when voters passed tax-limiting measures in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and 21 state legislatures enacted taxing or spending limits, according to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legislatures </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>. Some key tax issues facing voters this November: _ <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>: Dakota Proposition II would roll back property taxes on agricultural property to 1 percent of 1984 values, and 2.5 percent on non-agricultural property in stages by 1991 It would limit increases in property valuations to 2 percent a year. Local governments could impose special taxes if two-thirds of the voters approve. Supporters argue the state overrelies on property taxes and never lived up to promises to reform taxes after a similar ballot proposal was rejected in 1980. Opponents, including Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mickelson </PERSON>, cite a <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dakota </ORGANIZATION> study that warns that local governments stand to lose from $ 18 million to $ 112 million a year, and that schools would be hardest hit. _ <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>: Having survived legal challenges, Amendment 6, the so-called Taxpayers Bill of Rights Amendment, will appear on Nov. 8 ballots It would require voters to decide all future tax increases except in emergencies, would cut the income tax by about 10 percent and would limit residential property taxes to 1 percent of market value. Gov. <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Romer </PERSON> said the measure would be `` like throwing a bomb'' at state government. He and other political and business leaders who oppose the issue say it would cut state revenues by $ 65 million in the first year and $ 130 million the second. _ <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>: Voters face three tax initiatives that together would reduce state and local revenues by $ 329 million One would limit property taxes, a second would roll back 1987 tax hikes on income, sales, gasoline and cigarettes, and a third would give tax credits for private education. A poll this month forecast an uphill battle for the initiatives, which are opposed by Republican Gov. <PERSON> Norm </PERSON> <PERSON> Bangerter </PERSON>, his Democratic challenger <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, and a wide range of agriculture, education and wildlife groups. _ <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>: A tobacco industry-led coalition has spent $ 10 million to defeat Proposition 99, which would boost cigarette taxes for the first time since 1967, from 10 cents to 35 cents a pack Opponents call it an unfair tax that would trigger a wave of cigarette smuggling. The measure, which could raise $ 600 million a year, would finance anti-smoking programs in schools, medical care for the uninsured and tobacco-related medical research. It is backed by a variety of medical and health care groups as well as the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lung </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. _ <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>: The `` Fair Tax Amendment'' backed by Gov <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON> would make it easier for the Legislature to enact personal income tax increases. Income tax increases currently require a 75 percent majority vote in the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>; the amendment would lower that to 60 percent. The state has had an income tax since 1929 but it has been raised only once in history, in 1971. Anti-tax activists have filed a lawsuit challenging the amendment, and representatives of some business groups oppose the idea of making income tax increases easier. But <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON> said that if the amendment passes, the state `` will still be one of the hardest states in the country to raise a tax in.'' _ <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>: Question 9 on the ballot seeks to impose a constitutional ban on personal income taxes, even though the state does not have one The gaming industry is backing the measure on the theory that if new taxes ever became necessary, the measure would force the Legislature to look for other ways to spread the tax burden through corporate income taxes as well as existing property, sales and gaming-related taxes. They argue existing state taxes place too big a burden on the gambling industry while other forms of industry have relatively light tax loads.
