 The leader of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s main Christian militia has tightened his grip on power in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s beleaguered <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> enclave with the aid of <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and reportedly <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> as well. But <PERSON> Samir </PERSON> <PERSON> Geagea </PERSON> faces trouble with <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, which blames him for a political crisis that threatens to formally partition <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> and scuttle <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>'s hopes of controlling its unruly neighbor. <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> is also alarmed at political and military support for the Christians from <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, its archrival in the Arab world, after the Aug. 20 cease-fire in the Iraq-Iran war. <PERSON> Geagea </PERSON>, a 38-year-old <ORGANIZATION> Maronite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION>, sabotaged parliamentary efforts to elect a successor to President <PERSON> Amin </PERSON> <PERSON> Gemayel </PERSON> before his six-year term expired Sept. 23. He opposed Damascus-backed Christian candidates who he said would turn <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> into a `` Syrian satellite'' if elected. Under an unwritten law since <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> became independent from the French in 1943, <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s president has been a Christian. <PERSON> Geagea </PERSON>'s heavily armed Lebanese Forces militia, with about 6,000 hard-core fighters and 30,000 reservists, this month took over <PERSON> Gemayel </PERSON>'s 3,500-man militia and his news outlets and confined him to his east <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> home. <PERSON> Geagea </PERSON>, a former medical student, was left as the undisputed leader of the Christian enclave, home to about 800,000 Christians. Moslems make up about 55 percent of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s population. <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> newspapers have reported the Israelis, who occupy a borde