ped <PERSON> Gemayel </PERSON>. Tishrin, the Syrian government daily, accused the `` Geagea group'' of `` preventing <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> from achieving a constitutional presidential election ... and seeking the partition of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>.'' It warned that <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> `` will not allow any partition situation to be imposed.'' But after a 13-year civil war, <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> is a state in name only. The Syrians, the main power broker in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, want to impose a settlement through the election of a Christian ally who would reduce the Christians' traditional privileges and give the majority Moslems an equal share of political power. But <PERSON> Geagea </PERSON> and other right-wing Christians, who have seen their people driven out of the <LOCATION> Chouf </LOCATION> mountains and the coastal plain south of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> into the shrunken 390-square-mile enclave, reject any surrender of political power. <PERSON> Geagea </PERSON> favors a federal arrangement with the Moslems, who with the Syrians control about 70 percent of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. He has forged an alliance of expediency with <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>, another Maronite. But how long that will last is questionable. The two men long have distrusted each other, and their forces have skirmished repeatedly over the last three years. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>, 53, believes that some understanding must be reached with the Syrians, if only to get them out of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> has an estimated 40,000 troops in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, mostly in Moslem areas. Like the Israelis and the Americans, <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> has learned that intervening militarily in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> can be costly. In 1976, it tried to quell the civil war and wound up battling the Christians. But with <PERSON> Geagea </PERSON>'s power swelling, and outside powers using the Christians to thwart Syrian ambitions, <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>'s room to maneuver is diminishing.
</TEXT>
