<HEAD>Pope Marks 10th Anniversary, Beatifies Three 19th Century Priests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, marking the 10th anniversary of his papacy, beatified three 19th century priests Sunday and called for `` authentic sovereignty'' for <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> during a meeting with pilgrims. About 50,000 well-wishers carrying candles jammed St. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON>'s Square Sunday evening to take part in a prayer vigil and celebrate the anniversary The pope leaned out the window of his private studio and blessed them. `` Ten years ago the church of <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> received through divine providence the bishop that now thanks you, the man who came from afar,'' the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> said in Italian. `` He saluted you the first time with these words: Praised be <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Christ </PERSON>. I do that again this evening, and I salute, with you, the entire world.'' In the afternoon, he told 5,000 cheering Polish <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> officials and pilgrims at a <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> auditorium that `` the independence of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> can not be measured by geopolitical criteria, but only with the criteria of authentic sovereignty for the nation.'' His remarks, in Polish, were reported by the Italian news agency <ORGANIZATION> ANSA </ORGANIZATION>. The three who were made blesseds of the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> included the Rev. <PERSON> Venceslao </PERSON> <PERSON> Kozminiski </PERSON>, a Polish priest who founded 20 religious orders and associations; and two priests, the Rev. <PERSON> Bernardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Silvestrelli </PERSON> and the Rev. <PERSON> Carlo </PERSON> <PERSON> Houben </PERSON>. <PERSON> Kozminski </PERSON>, born Oct. 16, 1829, in <LOCATION> Biala </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Podlaska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, founded an order of nuns in 1855, three years after he became a priest. He founded a monastic order three years later and before he died had began 20 different religious congregations or orders. <PERSON> Silvestrelli </PERSON>, born in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> in 1831, headed the <LOCATION> Scala </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> -LRB- Holy Staircase -RRB- passion congregations for 25 years and under his direction the monastic order grew from six to 12 congregations. <PERSON> Houben </PERSON>, born in <LOCATION> Munstergeleen </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> in 1821, was sent to <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, where he spent much of his time as a missionary to coal miners. Beatification in the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> is a step toward possible sainthood. The ceremony Sunday took on added interest because it came on the anniversary of the day 10 years ago when <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> became the surprise choice of the conclave to succeed Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> I </PERSON>, who died after just 33 days on the throne of <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peter </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION>.
