<HEAD>Basque Separatists Blamed For Two Attacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PAMPLONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A car bomb exploded Sunday night as an armored car of the paramilitary civil guard passed by, killing one guard and injuring seven, police reported. They blamed Basque separatists for the attack and two other bombings that killed one person and injured three. Police said the car bomb contained up to 66 pounds of explosives and as many pounds of shrapnel. It exploded near the provincial jail in this northern city. The blast destroyed or damaged 15 parked cars and shattered windows in six apartment buildings. The slain guard was identified as <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> <PERSON> Gangoso </PERSON> <PERSON> Otero </PERSON>, 31, the driver of the armored car. Earlier Sunday a bomb exploded outside a tunnel near the railroad station of <LOCATION> Lepazpia </LOCATION> in northern <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, killing <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Pacheco </PERSON> <PERSON> Cano </PERSON>, 26, a member of the autonomous Basque police, and injuring three other people, according to police. They said a second bomb exploded inside the tunnel but caused no casulties. No group claimed responsibility but police suspected guerrillas of the Basque separatist group <ORGANIZATION> ETA </ORGANIZATION>, a Basque language acronym for Homeland and Liberty. The deaths brought to 13 the number of victims blamed on ETA this year. <ORGANIZATION> ETA </ORGANIZATION> has asserted responsibility for more than 600 killings, with most of the victims police and military officers, since it took up arms in 1986 to gain independence for the three-province Basque region in northern <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>.
