lthy, according to officials who admitted them to state juvenile facilities over the weekend. They spent Saturday talking with pediatricians, playing with donated teddy bears and enjoying peanut butter and jelly sandwiches, authorities said. `` The kids are starting to open up and have become fairly animated,'' he said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Carey </PERSON>, acting director of client services for the state Children's Services Division. `` They were quite hungry when they arrived. It seems that they only had a tomato apiece on Friday.'' The other three persons charged with murder are <PERSON> Constance </PERSON> <PERSON> Zipporah </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, 37, and <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Doolittle </PERSON>, 28, both of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chambers </PERSON>, 35, of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>. All four suspects were in custody Sunday at the county jail. Two other adults connected with <PERSON> Broussard </PERSON>'s group were charged with hindering prosecution and jailed in lieu of $ 100,000 bail each. <PERSON> Broussard </PERSON>, 35, was a star basketball player at <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Forest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grove </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, in the 1970s. He founded the controversial athletic association in 1975. The organization brought an estimated 70 to 100 men, women and children from <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> to the Sandy area in April 1987. They returned to <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> in June 1987 after neighbors opposed Ecclesia's applications for zoning permits to allow 55 children and 45 adults to live in tents and use portable toilets and showers.
