<TEXT>
 Five nuns remained locked inside the infirmary of their monastery Sunday to protest changes in their way of life, and no progress was reported toward a solution to the dispute. `` The television and radio reporters are all outside waiting around but basically everything's at a standstill today,'' said <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Sutton </PERSON>, a lay worker at the Roman Catholic Monastery of the Most Blessed <PERSON> Virgin </PERSON> <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carmel </LOCATION>. She has acted as a liaison between the nuns and the media. `` Nobody is speaking today,'' she said Sunday. `` We think it will be quiet until tomorrow.'' The changes made at the monastery include the introduction of sweets, radio and television. The five barricaded nuns think the 13 nuns at the monastery should strictly adhere to the traditional Carmelite life, which stresses prayer and silence. The nuns locked themselves in the monastery's infirmary on Oct. 4. They say they acted out of fear that the Diocese of <PERSON> Paterson </PERSON> would evict them. They have said they will not give up their vigil until their case is considered by the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, which under canon law is the official arbitrator in intra-order disputes. On Saturday, the Rev. <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Culligan </PERSON>, a Carmelite friar from <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, met with the sisters but was rebuffed when he could not prove through documents that he was the designated representative of the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> the nuns say they want. His official position gives him authority over Carmelite friars but no direct power over nuns of the order. Bishop <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodimer </PERSON>, head of the diocese, has said the nuns could be relieved of their vows for their actions.
