<HEAD>Manville Reports 3rd Qtr. Earnings</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Manville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, on the verge of emerging from six years of bankruptcy court protection, on Sunday reported its net income increased 9 percent in the third quarter as sales of the company's fiber glass and forest products rose For the quarter ended Sept. 30, Denver-based <ORGANIZATION> Manville </ORGANIZATION> said net income totaled $ 53.5 million, or $ 1.96 a share, up from $ 48.6 million, or $ 1.76 a share a year ago. Net sales during the period rose 7 percent to $ 584.3 million, from $ 547.9 million in the 1987 third quarter. <ORGANIZATION> Manville </ORGANIZATION> President and Chief Executive <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON> noted the positive performance `` was achieved despite the continued competitiveness in most construction related markets.'' Sales of the company's fiber glass and forest products rose 7 percent in the quarter. <ORGANIZATION> Manville </ORGANIZATION> filed for Chapter 11 protection in 1982 while being deluged with asbestos injury and property-damage lawsuits. By 1986, property damage claims alone had come to a staggering $ 85 billion, or about 40 times the company's total assets. The company also faced more than 17,000 personal injury claims in the billions of dollars. Earlier this month the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rejected the last challenge to <ORGANIZATION> Manville </ORGANIZATION>'s reorganization plan, virtually assuring the company's emergence from protection from its creditors under Chapter 11 of the Bankruptcy Code. The plan calls for establishing certain trusts to settle claims of asbestos health victims. `` With our strong operating performance and solid balance sheet, we're ready to exit Chapter 11 and move forward,'' <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON> said. For the first nine months, net earnings were $ 122.3 million, or $ 4.31 a share, down 8 percent from $ 132.6 million, or $ 4.73 a share. The current period includes certain charges and costs associated with the restructuring. Excluding the effects of the restructuring, <ORGANIZATION> Manville </ORGANIZATION> said net earnings would have totaled $ 136.2 million for the first nine months, compared with $ 120.1 million in the year-ago period. Net sales during the first nine months totaled $ 1.65 billion, up 7 percent from $ 1.54 billion in the year-ago period.
