<HEAD>What's So Rare as a Refrigerator? Try a Vacuum Cleaner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Refrigerators, irons, washing machines and a host of other electric appliances have vanished from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> stores partly because production has stagnated amid rising demand, a Soviet newspaper reported Sunday. The article in Trud, the labor daily, was the latest in a series of recent exposes on what the Soviets call `` deficits'' _ the disappearance of goods from stores. Muscovites are now coping with deficits on hard-to-find products ranging from razor blades to detergent. President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has said improving the array of goods and services available to Soviet consumers is necessary to show that his economic reform plan has taken root, but problems with both quality and quantity are still rife. The Trud report said that in some cases, Soviets are now buying 10 irons at a time when they appear on the market out of fear of future shortages. <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Korobkov </PERSON>, the head of a research institute on consumer demand, told the paper that rumors of a pending price rise linked to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms had triggered a buying boom. `` People have rushed to buy vacuum cleaners and refrigerators in reserve before they rise in price,''' <PERSON> Korobkov </PERSON> said. He also said economic cooperatives were buying up to 20 percent of some products, apparently also contributing to shortages. Production of many electric appliances has also stagnated, Trud said. The number of refrigerators produced is in a `` frozen state,'' the paper noted. Last year about the same number were built as in 1980. Trud said that of the 315,000 refrigerators needed to satisfy the anticipated demand in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> this year, orders had only been filled for 186,300. The capital received 258,000 vacuum cleaners, instead of the 540,000 needed, and only 804,000 irons, instead of the more than 1 million required, Trud said.
